	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Reports on the end of phase II negotiations</h1>

			
			<h4>
												31 October 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Speaking at the September 2005 negotiating session the Caribbean chief negotiator, Richard Bernal, said the ‘negotiations are poised to undergo a qualitative shift in specificity’. He set out three objectives for phase III: </p>
<ul>

<li> agreeing on the structure of an EPA; </li>

<li> consolidating outcomes on priority issues in regional integration; </li>

<li> agreeing on the approach to trade liberalisation, including sensitive products and best practices for private-sector operators and the business environment.</li>

</ul>
<p> He reaffirmed that EPAs must provide ‘a new development dynamic’, highlighting the importance of the basis of integration into the world economy as the key issue.</p><p> Phase III negotiations will be structured through four negotiating groups:</p>
<ul>

<li> market access; </li>

<li> services and investment; </li>

<li> trade-related issues; </li>

<li> legal and institutional questions.</li>

</ul>
<p> Chief negotiator Bernal characterised the second phase of negotiations as a ‘qualified success’. During this period some 11 specific proposals for strengthening regional integration had been forwarded to the EC for support.</p><p> This issue was taken up by the CARIFORUM ministerial spokesperson, Dame Billie Miller, who expressed disappointment at the EC’s failure to deliver on commitments on aid to support regional integration and to address supply-side constraints. The absence of Development Commissioner Michel from the ministerial meeting was seen as ‘particularly troubling’, since CARIFORUM had repeatedly highlighted the importance of ‘crafting an instrument for development-centred trade liberalisation’. Minister Miller highlighted ‘mounting concerns over the scope and pace of the adjustment process, which would result from the conclusion of an EPA with the EU’, particularly ‘the burden of financing economic restructuring and export diversification, while adjusting to the fiscal fallout from reduced tariffs’. She stressed that ‘given the adjustment process the region faces ... promised Commission support for advancing the regional-integration process and addressing supply-side constraints (must) begin to flow as soon as possible, and well before the scheduled conclusion of EPA negotiations at the end of 2007’. She argued that ‘the design of an EPA must take into consideration the differences in size and levels of development, between CARIFORUM and the EU’ and stressed that ‘the pace of what should be asymmetrical trade liberalisation must be set by CARIFORUM with clear exceptions for sensitive products’.</p><p> On substantive issues, chief negotiator Bernal spoke of the ‘scaling down’ of preferences in the Caribbean’s relationship with the EU and was critical of ‘fundamentalist free-trade policies that are eroding what little policy space small and vulnerable developing countries have left’. He argued that since the Caribbean’s share of global trade was negligible, the continuation of preferences could scarcely be seen as disruptive. He highlighted the region’s concerns over EU sugar-sector reform, proposals for a new tariff-only regime for bananas and the slow progress in the rum sector’s restructuring programme which was four years behind schedule.</p><p> In response to these concerns the EC expressed in a joint press release ‘a keen interest in working with CARIFORUM banana-supplying countries to obtain a fair and lasting solution’ and it ‘acknowledged the painful adjustment that will take place both in the Caribbean and Europe, as a result of proposed EU sugar reform’. The EC pledged to ‘work closely with CARIFORUM sugar-producing countries to assist them in coping with adjustment’.</p>
		
		
